{"title_page": "Bedford Hospital", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{for|the hospital in South Africa|Bedford Provincial Hospital (Eastern Cape)}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Bedford Hospital\n| Org/Group = [[Bedfordshire Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]\n| Image = Bedford-Hospital-Britannia-Road.jpg\n| image alt =\n| Caption = Bedford Hospital's Britannia Road entrance\n| map_type =Bedfordshire\n| map_caption=Location in Bedfordshire\n| Logo =\n| Logo Size =\n| Location = [[Bedford]]\n| Region = Bedfordshire\n| State = England\n| Country = United Kingdom\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.128857|-0.471743|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Funding = Public\n| Type = General\n| Speciality =\n| Standards =\n| Emergency = Yes\n| Affiliation =\n| Patron =\n| Network =\n| Beds =\n| Founded = 1897 ''(1803)''\n| Closed =\n| Website = {{url|bedfordhospital.nhs.uk}}\n| Wiki-Links = \n}}\n'''Bedford Hospital''' is a 400-bed district general hospital located in the English town of [[Bedford]], serving north and mid [[Bedfordshire]] run by Bedford Hospital NHS Trust.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bedford-A&E-ambulance.jpg|thumb|left|Accident & Emergency at the South Wing]]\n[[File:Bedford-Hospital-North-Wing.jpg|left|thumb|Gilbert Hitchcock House at the Bedford Health Village]]\n[[File:Bedford-Hospital-pathology.jpg|thumb|right|The new pathology building]]\nThe hospital was founded by [[Samuel Whitbread (1720\u20131796)|Samuel Whitbread]], the brewer, who had left \u00a38,000 in his will for the purpose of establishing a hospital.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/working-here/about-bedford-hospital/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The planning committee for the hospital, which included the [[John Russell, 6th Duke of Bedford|Duke of Bedford]], [[John Russell, 1st Earl Russell|Lord John Russell]] and the brewer\u2019s son, also [[Samuel Whitbread (1764\u20131815)|Samuel Whitbread]] made swift progress and the hospital opened in 1803.<ref name=history/>\n \nMajor recent developments have included the Cygnet Wing, which provides paediatric, maternity and gynaecology and which was opened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/news/sir-samuel-whitbread-21-years-as-bedfordshire-s-lord-lieutenant-1-3666395|title= Sir Samuel Whitbread: 21 years as Bedfordshire\u2019s Lord Lieutenant|date=8 April 2012|publisher=Bedford Today|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nIn 2001, it was reported in the local press that bodies were being stored on the floor of the chapel of rest, while part of the hospital's mortuary was undergoing maintenance. An internal inquiry found, that although the bodies were tampered with before the photographs were taken, the hospital's management was at fault, and the chief executive subsequently resigned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/1482654.stm |title=Bodies scandal 'was a set-up'|publisher=BBC News|date=9 August 2001|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nThe Primrose Centre for cancer patients was completed in 2003, the redevelopment of the pathology services unit was completed in 2006, a surgical assessment unit was completed in 2012 and an endoscopy unit was completed in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/working-here/about-bedford-hospital/|title=About us|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nThe Weller Wing, in which [[East London NHS Foundation Trust]] had provided [[psychiatry|psychiatric]] services, closed early in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mind-blmk.org.uk/news/weller-wing-closure-at-bedford-hospital|title=Weller Wing closure at Bedford Hospital|date=|publisher=Mind BLMK|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2017 plans were announced to merge the Bedford Hospital NHS Trust with [[Luton and Dunstable University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hospital seeks 'joyful' merger with teaching trust|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/bedford-hospital-nhs-trust/exclusive-hospital-seeks-joyful-merger-with-teaching-trust/7020549.article?|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Health Service Journal|date=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital operates from a series of sites:\n*Main site (South Wing): Bedford Hospital is mainly situated on Britannia Road/Ampthill Road in the [[Cauldwell, Bedfordshire|Cauldwell]] area of Bedford. This site (still popularly known as South Wing) is home to the [[Emergency department|Accident and Emergency department]], [[operating theatre|theatres]], [[pathology]], inpatient wards, [[radiology|x-ray department]], [[oncology]] services and the outpatients services. The main site houses BEDOC, NHS Bedfordshire CCG's [[General practitioner|GP]] out-of-hours emergency service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/BEDFORD17-NRTH-08_06-1.pdf|title=Map of Bedford Hospital (South Wing)|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n*Bedford Health Village (North Wing): Some services are based at the Bedford Health Village, two miles north of the main site. This site (which used to be known as North Wing) includes the old Bedford [[workhouse]] building. Services here include [[occupational therapy]], [[physiotherapy]] and rehabilitation facilities, as well as a chest clinic and a drop-in dental service.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-43582620|title=Millions to redevelop Bedford healthcare hub|date=28 March 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\n[[File:Bedford Hospital NHS Trust A&E performance 2005-18.png|thumb|Four-hour target in the emergency department quarterly figures from [[NHS England]] Data from https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/]]\n \nIn December 2013 it was announced that [[Monitor (NHS)|Monitor]] was reviewing of health services in Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes in an attempt to avert \"significant problems ahead\" in the local hospitals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor to review services in Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/5065795.article?WT.tsrc=Email&WT.mc_id=EditEmailStory&referrer=e2|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Health Service Journal|date=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n \n[[Circle Health]] was awarded a prime provider contract for Bedfordshire's Musculoskeletal service in April 2014 by the [[Clinical Commissioning Group]] and it was intended that the Trust would be a subcontractor. In November the Trust announced that it had refused to sign the contract because it endangered the viability of its trauma and Accident and Emergency service as the number of referrals dropped by 30%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bedford refuses to sign Circle MSK contract|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/hsj-local/acute-trusts/bedford-hospital-nhs-trust/bedford-refuses-to-sign-circle-msk-contract/5076545.article|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=Health Service Journal|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n \nIt was named by the [[Health Service Journal]] as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.  At that time it had 2211 full time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.96%. 75% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 63% recommended it as a place to work.<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ reveals the best places to work in 2015|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/best-places-to-work/hsj-reveals-the-best-places-to-work-in-2015/5087434.article|accessdate=23 September 2015|work=Health Service Journal|date=7 July 2015}}</ref> It spent 7.2% of its total turnover on agency staff in 2014/5.<ref>{{cite news|title=Agency spending: the real picture|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/hospitaltransformation/workforce/agency-spending-the-real-picture/7000191.article|accessdate=23 December 2015|work=Health Service Journal|date=26 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Healthcare in Bedfordshire]]\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n* [[List of NHS trusts]]\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n* [http://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/ Bedford Hospital NHS Trust website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090328110250/http://www.bedfordshirepct.nhs.uk/ Bedfordshire Primary Care Trust]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060512092619/http://www.blpt.nhs.uk/ Bedfordshire and Luton Mental Health and Social Care Partnership NHS Trust]\n* [http://www.hospitalradiobedford.org.uk/ Hospital Radio Bedford]\n \n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bedford]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{for|the hospital in South Africa|Bedford Provincial Hospital (Eastern Cape)}}\n{{Infobox hospital\n| Name = Bedford Hospital\n| Org/Group = Bedford Hospital NHS Trust\n| Image = Bedford-Hospital-Britannia-Road.jpg\n| image alt =\n| Caption = Bedford Hospital's Britannia Road entrance\n| map_type =Bedfordshire\n| map_caption=Location in Bedfordshire\n| Logo =\n| Logo Size =\n| Location = [[Bedford]]\n| Region = Bedfordshire\n| State = England\n| Country = United Kingdom\n| Coordinates = {{coord|52.128857|-0.471743|display=inline,title}}\n| HealthCare = NHS\n| Funding = Public\n| Type = General\n| Speciality =\n| Standards =\n| Emergency = Yes\n| Affiliation =\n| Patron =\n| Network =\n| Beds =\n| Founded = 1897 ''(1803)''\n| Closed =\n| Website = {{url|bedfordhospital.nhs.uk}}\n| Wiki-Links = \n}}\n'''Bedford Hospital''' is a 400-bed district general hospital located in the English town of [[Bedford]], serving north and mid [[Bedfordshire]] run by Bedford Hospital NHS Trust.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Bedford-A&E-ambulance.jpg|thumb|left|Accident & Emergency at the South Wing]]\n[[File:Bedford-Hospital-North-Wing.jpg|left|thumb|Gilbert Hitchcock House at the Bedford Health Village]]\n[[File:Bedford-Hospital-pathology.jpg|thumb|right|The new pathology building]]\nThe hospital was founded by [[Samuel Whitbread (1720\u20131796)|Samuel Whitbread]], the brewer, who had left \u00a38,000 in his will for the purpose of establishing a hospital.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/working-here/about-bedford-hospital/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> The planning committee for the hospital, which included the [[John Russell, 6th Duke of Bedford|Duke of Bedford]], [[John Russell, 1st Earl Russell|Lord John Russell]] and the brewer\u2019s son, also [[Samuel Whitbread (1764\u20131815)|Samuel Whitbread]] made swift progress and the hospital opened in 1803.<ref name=history/>\n \nMajor recent developments have included the Cygnet Wing, which provides paediatric, maternity and gynaecology and which was opened by [[Elizabeth II|the Queen]] in 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordtoday.co.uk/news/sir-samuel-whitbread-21-years-as-bedfordshire-s-lord-lieutenant-1-3666395|title= Sir Samuel Whitbread: 21 years as Bedfordshire\u2019s Lord Lieutenant|date=8 April 2012|publisher=Bedford Today|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref> \n \nIn 2001, it was reported in the local press that bodies were being stored on the floor of the chapel of rest, while part of the hospital's mortuary was undergoing maintenance. An internal inquiry found, that although the bodies were tampered with before the photographs were taken, the hospital's management was at fault, and the chief executive subsequently resigned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/1482654.stm |title=Bodies scandal 'was a set-up'|publisher=BBC News|date=9 August 2001|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nThe Primrose Centre for cancer patients was completed in 2003, the redevelopment of the pathology services unit was completed in 2006, a surgical assessment unit was completed in 2012 and an endoscopy unit was completed in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/working-here/about-bedford-hospital/|title=About us|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nThe Weller Wing, in which [[East London NHS Foundation Trust]] had provided [[psychiatry|psychiatric]] services, closed early in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mind-blmk.org.uk/news/weller-wing-closure-at-bedford-hospital|title=Weller Wing closure at Bedford Hospital|date=|publisher=Mind BLMK|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2017 plans were announced to merge the Bedford Hospital NHS Trust with [[Luton and Dunstable University Hospital NHS Foundation Trust]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hospital seeks 'joyful' merger with teaching trust|url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/bedford-hospital-nhs-trust/exclusive-hospital-seeks-joyful-merger-with-teaching-trust/7020549.article?|accessdate=9 October 2017|work=Health Service Journal|date=12 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\nThe hospital operates from a series of sites:\n*Main site (South Wing): Bedford Hospital is mainly situated on Britannia Road/Ampthill Road in the [[Cauldwell, Bedfordshire|Cauldwell]] area of Bedford. This site (still popularly known as South Wing) is home to the [[Emergency department|Accident and Emergency department]], [[operating theatre|theatres]], [[pathology]], inpatient wards, [[radiology|x-ray department]], [[oncology]] services and the outpatients services. The main site houses BEDOC, NHS Bedfordshire CCG's [[General practitioner|GP]] out-of-hours emergency service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/BEDFORD17-NRTH-08_06-1.pdf|title=Map of Bedford Hospital (South Wing)|publisher=Bedford Hospital|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n*Bedford Health Village (North Wing): Some services are based at the Bedford Health Village, two miles north of the main site. This site (which used to be known as North Wing) includes the old Bedford [[workhouse]] building. Services here include [[occupational therapy]], [[physiotherapy]] and rehabilitation facilities, as well as a chest clinic and a drop-in dental service.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-43582620|title=Millions to redevelop Bedford healthcare hub|date=28 March 2018|publisher=BBC|accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Performance==\n[[File:Bedford Hospital NHS Trust A&E performance 2005-18.png|thumb|Four-hour target in the emergency department quarterly figures from [[NHS England]] Data from https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/ae-waiting-times-and-activity/]]\n \nIn December 2013 it was announced that [[Monitor (NHS)|Monitor]] was reviewing of health services in Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes in an attempt to avert \"significant problems ahead\" in the local hospitals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Monitor to review services in Bedfordshire and Milton Keynes|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/5065795.article?WT.tsrc=Email&WT.mc_id=EditEmailStory&referrer=e2|accessdate=2 December 2013|newspaper=Health Service Journal|date=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n \n[[Circle Health]] was awarded a prime provider contract for Bedfordshire's Musculoskeletal service in April 2014 by the [[Clinical Commissioning Group]] and it was intended that the Trust would be a subcontractor. In November the Trust announced that it had refused to sign the contract because it endangered the viability of its trauma and Accident and Emergency service as the number of referrals dropped by 30%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bedford refuses to sign Circle MSK contract|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/hsj-local/acute-trusts/bedford-hospital-nhs-trust/bedford-refuses-to-sign-circle-msk-contract/5076545.article|accessdate=30 November 2014|work=Health Service Journal|date=7 November 2014}}</ref>\n \nIt was named by the [[Health Service Journal]] as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.  At that time it had 2211 full time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.96%. 75% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 63% recommended it as a place to work.<ref>{{cite news|title=HSJ reveals the best places to work in 2015|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/leadership/best-places-to-work/hsj-reveals-the-best-places-to-work-in-2015/5087434.article|accessdate=23 September 2015|work=Health Service Journal|date=7 July 2015}}</ref> It spent 7.2% of its total turnover on agency staff in 2014/5.<ref>{{cite news|title=Agency spending: the real picture|url=http://www.hsj.co.uk/hospitaltransformation/workforce/agency-spending-the-real-picture/7000191.article|accessdate=23 December 2015|work=Health Service Journal|date=26 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Healthcare in Bedfordshire]]\n* [[List of hospitals in England]]\n* [[List of NHS trusts]]\n \n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n==External links==\n* [http://www.bedfordhospital.nhs.uk/ Bedford Hospital NHS Trust website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090328110250/http://www.bedfordshirepct.nhs.uk/ Bedfordshire Primary Care Trust]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060512092619/http://www.blpt.nhs.uk/ Bedfordshire and Luton Mental Health and Social Care Partnership NHS Trust]\n* [http://www.hospitalradiobedford.org.uk/ Hospital Radio Bedford]\n \n[[Category:NHS hospitals in England]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Bedfordshire]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Bedford]]\n", "name_user": "Elshad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated trust", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bedford_Hospital"}
